05010nam a22007695i 9780231545006DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018004624  a97802315450067 a10.7312/corr183562doi  a(DE-B1597)514689  a(OCoLC)1083624083  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aRC455b.C67 2018 7aPSY0360002bisacsh04a362.196/892231 aCorrigan, Patrick, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Stigma Effect :bUnintended Consequences of Mental Health Campaigns /cPatrick Corrigan. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- t1. Who Is The Person With Serious Mental Illness? -- t2. What Is The Stigma Of Mental Illness? -- t3. Three Competing Agendas To Erase Stigma -- t4. It Is Much More Than Changing Words -- t5. Protest: Just Say No To Stigma -- t6. Beware The Educational Fix -- t7. Beating Stigma Person To Person -- t8. Lessons Learned For Future Advocacy -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite efforts to redress the prejudice and discrimination faced by people with mental illness, a pervasive stigma remains. Many well-meant programs have attempted to counter stigma with affirming attitudes of recovery and self-determination. Yet the results of these efforts have been mixed. In The Stigma Effect, psychologist Patrick W. Corrigan examines the unintended consequences of mental health campaigns and proposes new policies in their place.Corrigan analyzes the agendas of government agencies, mental health care providers, and social service agencies that work with people with mental illness, dissecting how their best intentions can misfire. For example, a campaign to change the language around mental illness by replacing supposedly stigmatizing words with empowering ones has made little difference in how people with mental health conditions are viewed. Educational programs that frame mental illness as a brain disorder have made the general public less likely to blame people for their illnesses, but also skeptical that such conditions can be cured. Ultimately, Corrigan argues that effective strategies require leadership by those with lived experience, as their recovery stories replace ideas of incompetence and dangerousness with ones of hope and empowerment. As an experienced clinical researcher, as an advocate, and as a person who has struggled with such prejudices, Corrigan challenges readers to carefully examine anti-stigma programs and reckon with their true effects.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMental illness. 0aSocial psychiatry. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Mental Health.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060660708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2019 Englishz978311061053608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2019z9783110606386oZDB-23-DPM40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/corr1835640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231545006423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231545006.jpg  a978-3-11-060660-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-061053-6  EBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb201